#create copy of original dataset
bikes = df.copy()

Change formats and create new columns¶

In [8]:
#change to datetime format
bikes['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bikes['start_time'])
bikes['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bikes['end_time'])

#extract date, hour, day of week, and day from start_time
bikes['start_date'] = bikes['start_time'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
bikes['start_hour'] = bikes['start_time'].dt.hour
bikes['start_day_of_week'] = bikes['start_time'].dt.strftime('%A')
bikes['start_day'] = bikes['start_time'].dt.day.astype(int)

#change id's to string
bikes['start_station_id'] = bikes['start_station_id'].astype('str')
bikes['end_station_id'] = bikes['end_station_id'].astype('str')

#change to categorical
bikes['user_type'] = bikes['user_type'].astype('category')
bikes['member_gender'] = bikes['member_gender'].astype('category')
bikes['bike_share_for_all_trip'] = bikes['bike_share_for_all_trip'].astype('category')

#create new column of duration in minutes
bikes['duration_min'] = bikes['duration_sec']/60

#create new column for age of members
bikes['member_age'] = 2019 - bikes['member_birth_year']

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 183412 rides from February of 2019 in the San Francisco area. Originally, there are 16 columns with data types of int, object, and float. The columns represent data such as: ride duration, start and end time, station name, id and location, bike id, whether user is a subscriber or customer, member birth year and gender.

I also created 2 new columns:

-age of users -age group of users -ride duration in minutes

What is/are the main features of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out about: -What days and hours are most popular for riders? -What is the difference in riding patterns between different categorical groups?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the columns such as duration, start time, week day, gender, user type and age will all be useful in finding interesting things from this dataset.

Univariate Exploration¶

What is the distribution of the age of riders?¶

In [174]:
#age of riders

plt.figure(figsize=[20,15])
plt.hist(bikes['member_age'], bins=100)

plt.xlabel('Age of Riders', size = 20)
plt.ylabel('Number of Rides', size = 20)

plt.xticks(size =15)
plt.yticks(size =15)

plt.title('Age of riders', size =30)
plt.show()

Most of the riders are definitely between 24 to 38, as they represent the largest peak in the histogram. Ages from 18 to 24 and 40 to 55 of riders take significantly less rides on these bikes. My interpretation is that people of about age 25 to 35 are in their prime working years but still young and energetic enough to take a bicycle to work. People who are younger tend not to have full time jobs and people who are older have less energy to ride bikes to work.¶

Which days of the week are the bikes most used?¶

Thursday is the day with the highest number of rides, followed by gradually lowering throughout wednesday, tuesday, monday and sunday. Saturday and Friday are have the lowest ride count. My interpretation of this is that Monday thur Thursday are working days, while people tend to exercise on Sundays. For Saturday and Friday, people may choose to take a vehicle as it is the start of the weekend.¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The main change thing I did was filter out the outliers of age, as someone who was 141 was skewing the distribution. 95% of riders were below 55 years old. So I grouped the ages accordingly from 15 to 55 years old in 4 groups.¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The main difference that I observed was the duration between subscribers and customers. There were alot more subscribers within the 2 to 10 minute mark with alot less above 10 minutes when compared to customers who were more even in their ride durations. The other small difference is that males have a lower riding duration than females, my interpretation is that males are stronger so they ride faster and require less time to reach their destination.¶

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I did not really see any other interesting relationships, as the age groups are all very similar in their ride durations.¶

Multivariate Exploration¶

Do subscribers and users differ in their usage throughout the days of the week?¶

In [166]:
# day_of_week, count, user_type
sb.set( rc = {'figure.figsize' : ( 30, 20 ), 
               'axes.labelsize' : 12 })
sb.set(font_scale = 2)

mv1 = sb.catplot(data=bikes, x='start_day_of_week', col="user_type", 
                 kind='count', sharey = False, height=7, aspect=11/7)

mv1.set_xticklabels(rotation=75);

mv1.fig.suptitle("Users difference in ride count in days of the week" ,
               fontsize = 'xx-large')
mv1.fig.subplots_adjust( top = 0.85 )

mv1.set_axis_labels( "Day of week" , "Ride count", size =20)


plt.show()

The days with biggest difference in ratio for customers are Sunday, and Saturday, where they have a more even ratio with the rest of the weekdays when compared to the subscribers, where their ride rate is alot lower when compare to weekdays. My intepretation is that subscribers are commuters who mostly use these bikes in for Monday to Friday for work, and by contrast, will ride them alot less on Sunday and Saturday. Customers are more even in their usage throughtout the week as they don't use them for commuting to work but for leisure.¶

               fontsize = 'x-large')

mv3.fig.subplots_adjust( top = 0.75 )

mv3.set_xticklabels(rotation=75);

plt.show()

Males and females do not differ much in their ride count through the days of the week, as they are both likely use these bikes for commuting to work. The other group varies a bit but it may be due to small sample size.¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Plotting the subscribers against the customers in hours of the day and days of the week showed the difference in usage of the bikes as the subscribers were more likely commuters who taking advantage of the benefits of being a subscriber, as their weekday usage is siginicantly higher when compared to their weekend usages. The customers usage were more consistent in all days of the week as they are more likely to be using the bikes for leisure whenever they want, and does not necessarily look for the benefits of subscribing. Plotting the age groups against one another also showed the high disparity in usage, as the younger groups with jobs are much more likely to use these as their main transportation.¶

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One thing that was very suprising was the substantially higher peak duration of usage by the 45-55 year old people during the hours of 1 am to 6 am. During this time, they also had the highest fluctuations in ride duration, as at 3am, their rides ranged from 7 minutes to 15 minutes. I am suprised people of that age group are riding bikes in those hours.¶
